  "line": 688,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "DELETE /api/v1/repos/:name",
  "rationale": "delete_repo computes `target = state_repos_dir.join(&name)` and pipes it straight to `std::fs::remove_dir_all` with no canonicalisation, no prefix check against state_repos_dir, and no rejection of `..` or absolute-path components. The `name` value is the URL segment, taken verbatim. The row-existence gate (`affected == 0` -> NotFound) does *not* keep traversal names out, because create_repo (router.rs:555) only rejects an empty `name` — it happily accepts `name = \"..\"`, `name = \"../..\"`, or an absolute path. The attack is two requests: (1) POST /api/v1/repos with `{\"name\":\"..\",\"source_kind\":\"local-path\",\"source_url_or_path\":\"/tmp\",\"i_own_this\":true}` to plant the row; (2) DELETE /api/v1/repos/.. — the row deletes, then `remove_dir_all(state_repos_dir/..)` recursively wipes the parent of nyx's state dir (sibling repo workspaces, the sqlite store, the operator's auth-token file, anything co-located). With `name = \"../../../etc\"`-style values the wipe walks farther. PathBuf::join does not normalise, and remove_dir_all follows `..` components via raw fs syscalls. Static pass missed this because the sink looks safe in isolation; the bug is the *missing* boundary check on a Path-extractor string the create handler already trusts.",
