  "rationale": "render_comment_body (pr_comment.rs:160-235) interpolates `report.run_id`, `report.since_ref`, every `row.repo`, `row.path`, `row.rule` and every `chain.id` raw into the markdown body that the bot POSTs to GitHub. The interpolations wrap most fields in backticks (e.g. `**`{repo}` / `{path}`**` at :196 and ``  - {severity_badge} {origin_badge} `{rule}`{line}{chain} - id `{id}` `` at :206-208), but a single literal backtick inside `path` or `rule` closes the inline-code span and lets any subsequent text inside the same field render as markdown. The `path` value is the on-disk filename of the offending source file (operator-controlled in the trusted case, but attacker-controlled whenever a hostile PR introduces a new file — exactly the contract the pr-comment subcommand runs under, by definition). The `rule` value is the rule id from the rule registry; mostly safe today, but the AI Exploration / NovelFinding writers can mint new rule strings (see candidate_findings.rule → findings.rule). GitHub markdown happily renders sanctioned HTML (`<img src=…>`, `<a href=…>`, blockquotes, headings) after a marker breakout, so a hostile filename like `evil\\`<a href=\"https://phish\">click for the real audit</a>\\`.py` lets an attacker put attacker-chosen content inside the bot's high-trust signed comment (the `<!-- nyx-agent:pr-comment v1 -->` marker reads to humans as 'this is the audit bot'). Static pass missed because the renderer treats the data as report text — the trust boundary (rendered-by-GitHub *as the bot*) is implicit, not in the type system. Suggested fix: escape backticks and angle brackets in repo/path/rule before interpolation, or wrap each field with a fenced code span using a dynamic fence length (`` ``` `` runs longer than any embedded backtick run).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "hostile branch: `mkdir -p \"src/\\`<a href='https://phish.example'>maintainer-approved fix</a>\\`/\"` then push a file under that dir whose contents trigger any rule; nyx-agent pr-comment renders the path into the body; GitHub renders the anchor inside the bot's signed comment."
}

notes (pass 3):
- COMMENT_MARKER source: src/cmd/pr_comment.rs (constant at module top, also embedded in tests/pr_comment_dedup.rs:47)
- find_existing_comment pagination: max 100 pages of 100 each = 10k comments; on a busier PR the marker is theoretically skipped and a duplicate posts. Lower-severity correctness bug, not raised separately.
- update_comment path /repos/<o>/<r>/issues/comments/:id requires bot ownership server-side; that asymmetry is what turns the marker-collision row above into a permanent silence rather than a comment-overwrite.
- pr_comment_dedup.rs (new test) exercises the create-then-update path against a wiremock GitHub but does not seed an attacker-authored marker comment, so the AUTH_BYPASS row above is currently *not* covered by the test contract.

