  "rationale": "Every `${{ inputs.* }}` reference in the composite Action is substituted by the GitHub Actions runner *before* bash sees the script, so the surrounding double-quotes are added literally after the value lands in the script body. Affected lines: 76-82 (`inputs.nyx-agent-binary`, `inputs.config`, `inputs.state-dir` via `steps.state.outputs.dir`, and the `--since-ref ${{ github.base_ref }}` arg), and 92-100 (same binary + config + state-dir, plus `inputs.ui-url`, `inputs.gh-api`, and `${{ github.event.pull_request.number }}`). Any input value containing `\"`, `$(...)`, or backtick syntax breaks out of the quoted arg and runs arbitrary code on the runner under the same shell as `GITHUB_TOKEN=${{ inputs.gh-token }}` (the env at line 73/88). The classic tj-actions/changed-files class. Concrete reach: a consumer workflow that wires `with: ui-url: ${{ github.event.pull_request.body }}` (or `gh-api`, or `config`) — a pattern operators *will* paste when they want the comment link to vary per-PR — gives any PR author RCE on the runner with the `pull-requests: write` token in scope. `github.base_ref` is normally repo-controlled (the target branch name), but `pull_request_target` workflows that fall back to `github.head_ref` for the diff base hand fork authors the same primitive without any consumer-side mistake; the head-ref name is fully attacker-controlled. Static pass missed because none of this is Rust — the sink is GHA expression substitution adjacent to a shell script with no `${{ env.NAME }}` indirection (the canonical mitigation: assign to env then reference `$NAME` so bash, not GHA, does the substitution).",
