record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": ".github/workflows/ci.yml",
  "line": 18,
  "cap": "SUPPLY_CHAIN",
  "endpoint": "<gha:rust job — install-action references>",
  "rationale": "ci.yml pins third-party Actions to mutable git refs: `taiki-e/install-action@nextest` (line 17) and `taiki-e/install-action@v2` (line 18) are tag names, not commit SHAs. Tags in GitHub are mutable — a maintainer (or an attacker who compromises the maintainer's GitHub credentials or push token) can move `@v2`/`@nextest` to any commit. The action runs in every CI job that processes a pull_request, and the job has no `permissions:` block at the workflow OR job level (the entire ci.yml file is missing top-level `permissions:`), so every step inherits the repository's *default* token scope — for most orgs that is `contents: read` + `metadata: read`, but the GitHub-org default of `read/write all` (still common on older orgs that have not flipped the org-wide setting in Settings → Actions → Workflow permissions) hands the compromised action a full-scope `GITHUB_TOKEN` for every PR build. Sibling actions are even more exposed: `actions/checkout@v4` (line 12), `dtolnay/rust-toolchain@stable` (line 13 — `@stable` is a branch, not even a tag), `Swatinem/rust-cache@v2` (line 16). The newly-added `taiki-e/install-action@v2` for sqlx-cli is the *additive* row this pass raises (the others were on the branch before), and it expands the trust surface: sqlx-cli is installed as a binary, then immediately run against the workspace, so a swapped-binary supply-chain attack lands code-exec inside the cache-warm runner where Cargo.toml secrets (CARGO_REGISTRY_TOKEN if present), rust-cache contents, and any GITHUB_TOKEN in scope are reachable. Distinct from the pass-5 row on .github/actions/nyx-agent/action.yml (that row is about argv-substitution inside the composite action's own bash steps; this row is about WHICH actions are loaded and with what immutability guarantees). Static pass missed because GitHub Actions YAML is not on the Rust source-pass input list, and the absence of SHA pinning is a missing invariant, not a tainted-flow signature. Fix: pin every third-party action to a 40-char commit SHA + comment with the human-readable tag for review (`uses: taiki-e/install-action@<sha> # v2.x.x`), add a top-level `permissions: contents: read` to ci.yml, and consider enabling Dependabot for the .github/workflows directory so the SHAs are tracked.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "n/a — defence is YAML hygiene. To reproduce the risk locally: clone taiki-e/install-action, push a new commit to a branch your CI follows, observe that the next PR build picks up the new code without any change to ci.yml. To audit the current state: `gh api repos/taiki-e/install-action/git/refs/tags/v2 --jq .object.sha` and confirm whether your CI's pinning matches that SHA at run time."
}

