{
  "path": ".github/workflows/ci.yml",
  "line": 35,
  "cap": "RACE_CONDITION",
  "endpoint": "<gha:rust job — `sqlx cache up-to-date` step>",
  "rationale": "The new `sqlx cache up-to-date` step uses a predictable absolute path under /tmp: `rm -f /tmp/sqlx-prepare.db` (line 35) then `export DATABASE_URL=\"sqlite:///tmp/sqlx-prepare.db?mode=rwc\"` (line 36). On GitHub-hosted Linux runners each job runs in a fresh ephemeral VM so the foot-gun is bounded, but the pattern is unsafe in three scenarios this repo will hit: (a) self-hosted runners — a single VM that processes multiple PR builds reuses /tmp across jobs; a prior job's leftover `/tmp/sqlx-prepare.db` (or a malicious symlink planted by a peer job sharing the runner) is consumed by the `rm -f` (rm follows the link's target, so `ln -s /home/runner/.cargo/credentials /tmp/sqlx-prepare.db` followed by an `rm -f` deletes the credentials file). (b) Local reproduction — operators replay the workflow under `act` or via `bash -c` from .github/workflows/ci.yml against their dev box; the fixed `/tmp/sqlx-prepare.db` collides with parallel `cargo sqlx prepare` invocations across worktrees / open repos / VS Code remote sessions. The `?mode=rwc` opens-or-creates, so the second invocation appears to succeed but writes into the wrong db; subsequent `cargo sqlx prepare --workspace --check` then *passes* on the wrong schema, masking a real drift. (c) The job has no `pull_request_target` guard, so a fork PR that edits `crates/nyx-agent-core/migrations/*.sql` runs the attacker's SQL during `sqlx migrate run --source ...` (line 38) inside the privileged runner. SQLite migrations can `ATTACH DATABASE '/home/runner/.cargo/credentials' AS leak;` and dump its contents into a temp table that the runner subsequently uploads as an artifact / writes to stdout in the next build step. ATTACH does not require any special permission and SQLite happily opens any file the runner uid can read. Distinct from the pass-5 OS_COMMAND row on the composite action (that one targets `${{ inputs.* }}` substitution; this one targets attacker-authored SQL files committed to a fork PR). Static pass missed because (i) sqlx-cli's migration execution is a black-box subprocess, (ii) the SQL file source is the source tree, not a tainted-flow string. Fix: (1) use `${{ runner.temp }}/sqlx-prepare.db` instead of `/tmp/...` — runner.temp is unique-per-job; (2) add `permissions: contents: read` at workflow scope so a compromised migration cannot write back; (3) for pull_request_target compatibility, restrict the `sqlx cache up-to-date` step to `if: github.event_name == 'push'` so only trusted post-merge commits run unreviewed SQL; (4) add `--locked` to any cargo install steps so dependency lock isn't drifted under the runner.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Self-hosted runner repro: as a peer-job process on the runner, `ln -s /home/runner/.bash_history /tmp/sqlx-prepare.db && sleep 60` immediately before the rust job's `rm -f` fires; observe the target file disappear after `rm -f` follows the symlink. Fork-PR SQL repro: open a PR adding `crates/nyx-agent-core/migrations/9999_leak.sql` containing `ATTACH DATABASE '/home/runner/.cargo/config.toml' AS leak; CREATE TABLE exfil AS SELECT * FROM leak.sqlite_master;` (sqlite quietly stores the file's first 100 pages as table rows accessible to a follow-on step or to the cache layer)."
}

