{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-core/src/state.rs",
  "line": 65,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "endpoint": "<core:StateDir::project_repos(project_id)>",
  "rationale": "New `project_repos` helper builds `self.root.join(\"projects\").join(project_id).join(\"repos\")` with no validation of `project_id`. The `ProjectId` newtype (project/mod.rs:15-23) is a raw `String` wrapper — `ProjectId::new` does no sanitisation, accepts `..`, `/`, `..\\`, and the empty string. Two Rust `Path::join` footguns detonate here: (1) `PathBuf::join` with an absolute path *replaces* the prefix, so `project_id = \"/etc\"` yields `/etc/repos` and `project_id = \"/var/root/.ssh\"` would write a workspace tree at `/var/root/.ssh/repos/<name>/`; (2) relative `..` segments stack against `<state>/projects/` — `project_id = \"../../tmp/foo\"` escapes both `projects/` and `state/` to land at `<state-parent-parent>/tmp/foo/repos/`. The caller is `main.rs drive_scan` at line 460 (`let state_repos = state_dir.project_repos(repo.project_id.as_str())`) and the value flows directly into `ingest(repo, &state_repos, &run.id)` which calls fs::create_dir_all + git clone. Today the ProjectId is set by `upsert_repo_record` which preserves the existing row's project_id else assigns DEFAULT_PROJECT_ID (router.rs:567), so the attack surface is gated on whether ProjectId can be operator-supplied — and it can: `ProjectStore::create` (store/project.rs:57) takes `id: &str` with zero validation and any future `[[project]]` TOML block (Phase 3) or `POST /api/v1/projects { id }` route (Phase 5, already commented at router.rs:563) lands the primitive. Even today the SQLite row id field accepts any UTF-8, so an operator with write access to `state.sqlite` (no escalation needed — operator already owns the file under `i_own_this` semantics) can set `projects.id = '../../etc/cron.d'` and the next `nyx-agent scan` will `ingest` (git clone) into `/etc/cron.d/repos/<name>/` running as the daemon user. The static pass missed this because (a) `Path::join` is not in any tainted-sink ruleset — it's the *absorbing-absolute-path* and *parent-escape* semantics that are the bug, not a sink call; (b) the ProjectId newtype gives a false sense of validation. Fix: validate ProjectId at the constructor — reject empty, anything containing `/`, `\\`, `..`, NUL, or any byte < 0x20; reject leading `.`; cap length at e.g. 64; restrict to `[A-Za-z0-9_-]` (matches the seeded `default-project`). Apply the same constraint in the SQLite schema (CHECK constraint on `projects.id`) and in `ProjectStore::create`. Also harden `StateDir::project_repos` to canonicalise + assert the result starts with `self.root` before returning; today there is no defence-in-depth guard.",
