{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-core/src/store/spec.rs",
  "line": 80,
  "cap": "DATA_TAMPERING",
  "endpoint": "<store-api: harness_specs().insert_with_finding_spec_link>",
  "rationale": "The new helper advertises an atomic dual-write (`harness_specs` INSERT + `findings.spec_id`/`attack_provenance`/`prompt_version` UPDATE inside one tx) so SpecDerivation cannot leak orphans. The INSERT side is safe but `harness_specs` carries NO finding-side FK — the back-link lives on `findings.spec_id` (migrations/0002_specs.sql:23, ON DELETE SET NULL). The UPDATE at spec.rs:80 binds `WHERE id = ?finding_id`; when that row does not exist sqlite returns 0 rows affected, NOT an error, and the tx commits with the spec persisted but the finding never stamped. The partner test at spec.rs:170-201 EXPLICITLY documents this — `err.expect(\"first call succeeds (UPDATE matches zero rows)\")` is in-tree as accepted behaviour. Net effect: (1) callers cannot tell from `Ok(())` whether the stamp actually landed, defeating the very invariant the helper exists to enforce; (2) the `harness_specs` table accumulates orphan rows whose `spec_blob` (the YAML/JSON the runtime later feeds to the shell/python harness templates at ai_pipeline.rs:1744) is unreachable through findings.spec_id but still listable by `list_by_cap` (spec.rs:155 in the existing tests) — operator-facing summaries that aggregate by cap silently double-count or surface specs detached from any finding. Worse path: the helper is called from ai_pipeline.rs:665 with `finding_id` taken from the candidate-finding promotion path; if a TOCTOU race between SpecDerivation completion and a parallel finding-deletion / supersede flow lands the UPDATE on a row that has already gone (e.g. run cascade-deleted while spec derivation was in flight), the spec row stays in the DB carrying attacker-influenced `spec_blob` (LLM output from the candidate's `suggested_payload_hint`) and zero linkage telling the operator where it came from. Distinct from the payload helper because the payload row would FK-fail at INSERT under the same race; spec helper does not. Static pass missed this because (a) the static walker treats the second `sqlx::query(...).execute(&mut *tx)` as a write that returns Result and trusts the `await?` to surface failures, blind to the SQL semantics of zero-row UPDATEs, and (b) the test partner asserts the broken behaviour as intent, so a tests-first walker concludes the code is correct. Severity: data-integrity / provenance-tracking corruption — not RCE on its own, but it defeats the audit trail rows 1-14 assume is present when triaging AI-sourced findings, so any incident response that filters on `findings.attack_provenance IS NOT NULL` will miss the very rows the helper was meant to mark.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "1) Repro the silent failure: `cargo test -p nyx-agent-core -- store::spec::tests::insert_with_finding_spec_link_rolls_back_when_finding_missing` — observe the first call returns Ok(()) while the harness_specs table holds an orphan. 2) Defence: capture the UPDATE's `rows_affected()` (sqlx `QueryResult::rows_affected()`) and return `StoreError::NotFound(finding_id)` when it equals 0, then bubble that error out of `apply_spec_outcome` in ai_pipeline.rs:660-666 so the apply path logs or retries instead of marking the trace as Synthesised. 3) Belt-and-braces: add a CHECK or migration step asserting `harness_specs.id ∈ findings.spec_id` (correlated subquery / trigger) before the next schema bump."
}

