{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent-sandbox/src/workspace.rs",
  "line": 73,
  "cap": "PATH_TRAVERSAL",
  "rationale": "Snapshot copies symlinks verbatim and relies on every downstream consumer to canonicalise. `copy_tree` (workspace.rs:70-99) and `reflink_tree` (workspace.rs:136-163) both branch on `meta.file_type().is_symlink()` and reproduce the symlink with `std::os::unix::fs::symlink(&target, dst)?` regardless of whether the target points inside the workspace root. The module doc claims `a symlink pointing outside the workspace stays an unreachable pointer rather than getting materialised into a real file under the snapshot` — that is only true when every reader of the snapshot uses `symlink_metadata` + an explicit canonicalise-and-fence check. The shim binary (sandbox/src/shim.rs) and chain_runner (sandbox/src/chain_runner.rs:425, already row 21) demonstrate the risk pattern: a single `fs::read_to_string(workspace.join(user_supplied_rel))` that resolves through the symlink reads `/etc/passwd` or any file the agent uid can open. The kernel's bind-mount fence (when enabled) blocks the read, but on the macOS dev-loop path and the chain-lane workspace fast path there is no kernel-level containment, only the symlink-aware-or-not behaviour of each Rust caller. The static pass misses because workspace.rs itself does nothing wrong syntactically — the bug is the unverified contract on every consumer.",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "Stage a source workspace with `ln -s /etc/passwd ./escape`. Call `snapshot(src, dst)` — the snapshot now contains `dst/escape -> /etc/passwd`. Then exercise any chain-lane payload that does `fs::read_to_string(workspace_root.join(rel))` where `rel` is `escape` (the existing payload_runner.rs:236 row 22 already shows this pattern). Fix in workspace.rs: when copying a symlink, canonicalise `target` and reject (or rewrite to a sentinel broken link) anything whose canonical form does not start with `src`. Belt-and-braces: have the sandbox kernel mount the snapshot read-only with `nosymfollow` (Linux 5.10+) or wrap every snapshot consumer behind a single `safe_join` helper that refuses paths escaping the root."
}

